1 Burnt area detection of Torre de lEspanyol Forest Fire

In this exercise, we will delineate the area affected by a wildfire in Torre de lEspanyol (Tarragona, attached map) that took place by the end of June 2019, and burnt 4,000 ha of forests, and 1,000 ha of agricultural lands. Before the fire, the area was mainly covered by Aleppo pine woodlands, interspersed with olive and almond cultures, and rainfed crops. For more information, please check this press article

1.1 Download data

To outline the burnt area, we will use the atmospherically and geometrical corrected Landsat 8 images. For downloading, we will access it from the Earth explorer portal. From there, we retrieve the pre-fire image LC08_L2SP_198031_20190526_20200828_02_T1 and postfire LC08_L2SP_198031_20190729_20200827_02_T1. After downloading, unzip the folders using 7zip.

1.2 Load libraries or install if necessary

We use spatial R libraries such as rgdal, sp, rgeos & raster to process spatial information. This piece of code loads the libraries or installs them if are not installed.

if(!require("rgdal")) install.packages("rgdal")

1.3 Bands and information

Each image offers the different spectral bands, that have registered in several spectrum regions. Furthermore Collection 2 - Level 2 Landsat data offers several extra information derived from correction process. This information could be useful to filter pixels under different purposes or scientific contexts.

QA_PIXEL: Pixel quality
QA_RADSAT: Radiometric Saturation Quality Assessment band
SR_QA_AEROSOL: Surface Reflectance Quality Assessment Band
ST_QA: Surface Temperature Quality Assessment Band
ST_CDIST: Pixel distance to cloud
ST_ATRAN: Atmospheric Transmittance
ST_DRAD: Downwelled Radiance
ST_EMIS: Emissivity of Band 10 estimated from ASTER GED
ST_EMSD: Emissivity standard deviation
ST_TRAD: Thermal band converted to radiance
ST_URAD: Upwelled Radiance

1.5 Boundary box of study area

Here we create a bbox of study area to simplify processes and reduce time consuming.

xmax <- 303478.3
xmin <- 291688.5 
ymax <- 4580423
ymin <- 4564463 
coords = matrix(c(xmin, ymin,
                  xmin, ymax,
                  xmax, ymax,
                  xmax, ymin,
                  xmin, ymin), 
                ncol = 2, byrow = TRUE)


P1 = Polygon(coords)
SA = SpatialPolygons(list(Polygons(list(P1), ID = "a")), proj4string=CRS("+proj=utm +zone=31 +datum=WGS84 +units=m +no_defs"))
plot(SA,axes = TRUE)

1.7 Normalized Burn Ratio (NBR)

The Normalized Burn Ratio (NBR) is an index designed to highlight burnt areas in large fire zones. This index uses NIR band to capture vegetation vigor reflection and SWIR to measure the moisture absorvance. When a fire occurs, plant vigor is reduced, and consequently the NIR wavelengths are absorbed. Moisture contents are also reduced, in this way, r the energy captured in the SWIR spectral region is reflected (Fig. 1).

Figure 1: Vegetation spectral response pre and post fire

The formula of Normalized Burn Ratio \((NBR)\) is the normalized ratio between Near infrared (NIR) and Short Wavelength Infrared (SWIR2)

\[ nbr = \frac{\rho_{850}-\rho_{2200}}{\rho_{850}+\rho_{2200}}=\frac{NIR-SWIR_2}{NIR+SWIR_2}=\frac{Band_5-Band_7}{Band_5+Band_7} \]

The difference between the pre-fire and post-fire \(NBR\) is used to calculate the delta NBR \((\Delta{NBR})\), which then can be used to estimate the burn severity.

\[ \Delta{NBR}=NBR_{pre fire}-NBR_{post fire} \]

##NIR and SWIR band selection
NIR.pre <- img.pre$LC08_L2SP_198031_20190526_20200828_02_T1_SR_B5
SWIR.pre <- img.pre$LC08_L2SP_198031_20190526_20200828_02_T1_SR_B7

##NBR pre Calculation
nbr.pre <- (NIR.pre-SWIR.pre)/(NIR.pre+SWIR.pre)

##NIR and SWIR band selection
NIR.post <- img.post$LC08_L2SP_198031_20190729_20200827_02_T1_SR_B5
SWIR.post <- img.post$LC08_L2SP_198031_20190729_20200827_02_T1_SR_B7

##NBR pre Calculation
nbr.post <- (NIR.post-SWIR.post)/(NIR.post+SWIR.post)

##dNBR calculation and scale to 1000
dNBR <- (nbr.pre-nbr.post)*1000

#Plot results
plot(dNBR)

1.8 Vectorize perimeters

Following \(\Delta{NBR}\) values expressed in Table 1, burnt pixels are those that have a \(\Delta{NBR} >100\). In the next piece of code we set as NA the values lower than 100 and as 1 the greater ones. Therefore, we obtain Burnt Area Raster.

Table 1: Burn severity levels obtained calculating dNBR, proposed by USGS
Severity Level dNBR Range
Enhanced Regrowth, high -500 to -251
Enhanced Regrowth, low -250 to -101
Unburned -100 to 99
Low Severity 100 to 269
Moderate-low Severity 270 to 439
Moderate-high Severity 440 to 659
High Severity 660 to 1300 
dNBR[dNBR<100] <- NA
dNBR[!is.na(dNBR)] <- 1

plot(dNBR)

Whenever we have the Burnt Area Raster, we vectorize it to obtain the fire permimeter.

pol <- rasterToPolygons(dNBR,dissolve = T)


perimeter <- as(pol,"SpatialLinesDataFrame")
plot(perimeter)

1.9 Mapping our results

Additionaly, we can map our results using leaflet library wit the following code

leaflet(spTransform(perimeter,CRSobj = CRS("+init=epsg:4326")))%>%
  addTiles(group = "OSM (default)")%>%
  addProviderTiles(providers$Esri.WorldImagery,group = "Imagery")%>%
  addPolylines(color = "red", group = "Perimeter",opacity = 1,weight = 0.5)%>%
  addRasterImage(projectRaster((nbr.pre-nbr.post)*1000, crs=CRS("+init=epsg:4326")),group = "dNBR")%>%
  addLayersControl(
    baseGroups = c("OSM (default)", "Imagery"),
    overlayGroups = c("Perimeter", "dNBR"),
    options = layersControlOptions(collapsed = FALSE)
  )
